## 15. Auth Change-Control (MANDATORY for any change in the AUTH domain)

The AUTH domain is the most blast-prone surface in the EM Ecosystem: a wrong
edit can silently disable login, leak tokens, or break MFA / OAuth flows for
every downstream consumer. This section is the single source of governance
for every change that touches AUTH. It complements `.github/CODEOWNERS`
(which enforces review) with the process gates that surround it.

### 15.1 Domain definition

A change is "in AUTH" if it modifies any of the following paths. The list
is derived from the AUTH inventory dated 2026-05-14 and matches the
`.github/CODEOWNERS` blocks assigned to `@emillionnetworking`:

| Path | Scope |
|---|---|
| `<workspace.backend_root>/auth/` | Full module: controllers (`auth`, `account`, `mfa`, `oauth`, `passkey`, `session`), services (`login`, `login-security`, `token`, `token-deny-list`, `mfa`, `passkey`, `oauth-auth`, `password-reset`, `password-breach`, `email-verification`, `trusted-device`), guards (`jwt`, `jwt-or-mfa-setup`, `mfa-setup`, base/google/github OAuth, `oauth-link`, `oauth-callback.filter`, `roles`, `permissions`), strategies (`jwt`, `google`, `github`, `oauth-validate`, `pkce`), stores (`oauth-code`, `oauth-link-code`, `oauth-state`), `dto/`, `constants/`, `interfaces/`, `utils/`, `tests/` |
| `<workspace.backend_root>/config/auth.config.ts` | AUTH runtime config |
| `<workspace.backend_root>/config/oauth.config.ts` | OAuth provider config |
| `<workspace.backend_root>/common/interfaces/authenticated-request.interface.ts` | Express request shape used by AUTH guards |
| `<workspace.backend_root>/common/interfaces/jwt-payload.interface.ts` | JWT contract |
| `<workspace.backend_root>/common/interfaces/oauth-profile.interface.ts` | OAuth profile contract |
| `<workspace.backend_root>/common/utils/cookie.util.ts` | Session / refresh cookie helpers |
| `<workspace.backend_root>/types/express.d.ts` | Express ambient types extended by AUTH |
| `<workspace.backend_root>/users/enums/provider.enum.ts` | OAuth provider enum (lives in `users/`, semantically AUTH) |

### 15.2 What is NOT AUTH

The following modules interact with AUTH but are governed by their own
owners and lifecycles. Editing them in isolation is NOT covered by this
section (but a change that ALSO touches a §15.1 path triggers Rule
15.3.4 below):

- `<workspace.backend_root>/sessions/` — sessions domain
- `<workspace.backend_root>/permissions/` — RBAC domain (consumed by AUTH guards)
- `<workspace.backend_root>/security/` — CSRF, Turnstile, suspicious-login, security config
- `<workspace.backend_root>/audit/` — audit logging
- `<workspace.backend_root>/mail/` — cross-domain templates (auth, security, users-security, audit)
- `<workspace.backend_root>/users/` (everything except `enums/provider.enum.ts`) — users-security + admin CRUD
- `<workspace.backend_root>/common/guards/csrf.guard.ts`, `common/guards/custom-throttler.guard.ts`
- `<workspace.backend_root>/common/decorators/roles.decorator.ts`, `common/decorators/permissions.decorator.ts`
- `<workspace.backend_root>/common/middleware/helmet.middleware.ts`, `common/middleware/https-redirect.middleware.ts`
- `<workspace.backend_root>/common/services/crypto.service.ts` (and its module)
- `<workspace.backend_root>/geolocation/`
- `<workspace.frontend_root>**` — UI (excluded from AUTH ownership by explicit policy)

### 15.3 Mandatory rules

1. **No AUTH change without an explicit Jira ticket.** The ticket key
   MUST appear in the branch name, commit subject, and PR title. A
   commit-only or branchless edit to a §15.1 path is a Scope-Gap (§8)
   and blocks merge.
2. **No AUTH change merges without owner approval.** The owner is
   `@emillionnetworking` per `.github/CODEOWNERS`. GitHub enforces this
   via CODEOWNERS-required review on branch-protected `main` (§2
   Required Repository Configuration B); the `/commit` step MUST NOT
   bypass or self-approve. Approval applies per PR — past approvals do
   not generalise.
3. **Every AUTH PR MUST include three artifacts**, produced during
   `/plan` and `/verify`:
   - **Impact analysis** — blast radius per §9 (Regression Protection),
     listing every §15.1 file transitively affected plus every external
     module that imports the modified AUTH symbols.
   - **Rollback plan** — a written procedure to revert the change
     without leaving partial state in production (token store, cookie
     format, DB column, OAuth registration). DB-touching changes MUST
     be backward-compatible per §9 Breaking Change Checklist.
   - **Explicit verification** — the `/verify` report MUST list the
     AUTH test files exercised (`<workspace.backend_root>/auth/tests/*.spec.ts`),
     classify any deviation per §8 (see §15.4 for the default class),
     and confirm the build runs clean against the full AUTH suite — not
     a subset.
4. **Cross-domain changes split into two PRs.** A PR that touches a
   §15.1 path AND a path listed in §15.2 MUST be split: one PR for the
   AUTH portion (owned by `@emillionnetworking`), one PR for the
   non-AUTH portion (owned by its domain owner). Atomic cross-domain
   merges are forbidden because they make the AUTH review surface
   uninspectable and bypass the per-domain owner.
   - Exception: a PR whose ONLY non-AUTH change is updating a downstream
     consumer required for the AUTH change to compile (e.g. a single
     import update) MAY remain a single PR if the non-AUTH owner is
     listed as additional reviewer.
5. **Ambiguity is escalated, not assumed.** If a developer is unsure
   whether a file belongs to AUTH (typical cases: anything under
   `common/` not listed in §15.1, anything in `users/` other than
   `enums/provider.enum.ts`, anything in `mail/templates/` related to
   login or password), they MUST ask the AUTH owner BEFORE editing.
   Editing first and reclassifying after is forbidden because it
   leaves half-reviewed AUTH state in the history.

### 15.4 Interaction with §8 Deviation Classification

Every deviation in an AUTH PR is treated as **Accepted-Risk** by default
(§8) unless the owner explicitly downgrades it during `/verify`. No AUTH
deviation can land silently as Accepted-Trivial or Accepted-Quality —
the owner must classify it after seeing the formal risk analysis
required by §8 "Accepted-Risk Requirements" (risk description,
compensating controls, residual risk, follow-up ticket if residual >
LOW).

### 15.5 Anti-Patterns

- "Small AUTH tweak" merged without a Jira ticket because "it's just a
  log message" — a Scope-Gap regardless of size; AUTH has no trivial
  surface.
- Bundling a `users/users.controller.ts` admin-CRUD edit and an
  `auth/account.controller.ts` edit in one PR — violates §15.3.4
  (users-security and AUTH must split).
- Reclassifying an AUTH deviation as Accepted-Trivial during `/verify`
  to skip the formal risk analysis — forbidden by §15.4.
- Adding a new file under `<workspace.backend_root>/auth/` and only listing
  the test file in the implementation record — the new source file is
  AUTH-owned and MUST surface in the PR's blast radius (§9).
- Touching `<workspace.backend_root>/users/enums/provider.enum.ts` from a
  non-AUTH ticket on the assumption it lives in `users/` — its
  semantic owner is AUTH (§15.1).

### 15.6 Cross-references

- `.github/CODEOWNERS` — enforcement layer for Rule 15.3.2.
- §2 Branch Lifecycle — Definition of DONE; AUTH tickets inherit it
  unchanged.
- §3 Sequential Ticket Workflow — Known Dependency Patterns table
  already documents `JwtAuthGuard`, `RolesGuard`, `PermissionsGuard`;
  AUTH changes that alter those guards MUST update that table.
- §8 Deviation Classification — `/verify` runtime classes; §15.4
  refines the default for AUTH.
- §9 Regression Protection — blast radius and Breaking Change
