- `forge/specs/integration-state.md` — read before planning any
  AUTH change to see which downstream modules import AUTH symbols.
- AUTH domain inventory (2026-05-14) — original mapping that produced
  the path list in §15.1 and the exclusions in §15.2.

## 16. Framework Versioning (MANDATORY for any change to schemas, skills, or tooling contracts)

The framework declares a Semantic Version 2.0.0 in the `VERSION` file at
the repository root. This is the canonical record of "framework state at
time T" and the basis for retrospective queries like *which framework
version produced <TICKET-ID>?*.

Introduced by <TICKET-ID> to close audit FU-related gap G10 (no framework
versioning, audit `13-memory-knowledge-integration.md (§memory-integration)`).

### 16.1 SemVer bump rules

| Bump | Trigger |
|---|---|
| **X (major)** | Breaking schema change — existing plan/verify/record artifacts would FAIL validation under the new schema. Breaking skill change — lifecycle gate behaviour changes (e.g. `/verify` adds a new mandatory verdict). Removal of a public tool from `forge/tools/`. |
| **Y (minor)** | Non-breaking additions — new optional schema field, new skill, new tool, new ADR, new spec under `forge/specs/`. The <TICKET-ID> schema additions themselves are a Y bump. |
| **Z (patch)** | Typo / format / clarification with zero semantic impact — README correction, comment cleanup, formatting fix. |

### 16.2 When to bump

- At `/commit` time of any ticket that touches schemas, skills, or tooling
  contracts (i.e. the artifacts listed in §16.1 triggers).
- The version bump is part of the SAME PR as the change that justifies it.
- Operator/AI edits `VERSION` directly; commits alongside the
  schema/skill/tool change. Cannot defer to a separate PR.

### 16.3 Where to record the bump

- Record §8 "Documentation Updates" MUST list `VERSION` if it was bumped.
- The record body explicitly states the new version (`Bumped VERSION
  from 0.5.0 to 0.6.0 — Y bump (new optional field in plan schema)`).
- Optional: record §11 Recommended Follow-ups may note follow-on
  versioning actions.

### 16.4 Frontmatter usage in lifecycle artifacts

- Plan / verify / record artifacts MAY include `framework_version: X.Y.Z`
  in frontmatter (additive optional field, declared in the respective
  schema under `frontmatter.properties`).
- Tooling reads this for retrospective queries; no current consumer is
  blocking on its presence.
- Pre-<TICKET-ID> artifacts and <TICKET-ID> itself do NOT carry this field
  (the schema-change PR cannot self-reference a field that doesn't yet
  exist pre-merge — chicken-and-egg). First artifact in the corpus to
  use the field is <TICKET-ID> onwards.

### 16.5 Naming collision with `audit-phase-report.schema.yml`

The `framework_version` field already existed in
`forge/_parked/schemas/audit-phase-report.schema.yml (parked per ADR-010)` BEFORE <TICKET-ID>, with a
different semantic:

| Schema | Field semantic | Example value | Established by |
|---|---|---|---|
| `audit-phase-report.schema.yml` | Version of the AUDIT framework standards | `audit-standards.mdc v1.0` | Pre-existing (Phase 12-15 audit tools) |
| `plan.schema.yml` / `verify.schema.yml` / `record.schema.yml` | SemVer of em-development-framework | `0.5.0` | <TICKET-ID> |

Both names live in their own schema and apply only in that schema's
artifacts. No migration of audit-phase reports is performed. Tooling that
reads either field must be schema-aware (consult the artifact's
`schema:` frontmatter field before interpreting `framework_version`).

### 16.6 Git tagging — operator action

After a PR that bumps `VERSION` merges to `main`, the operator MUST tag
the merge commit:

```bash
git tag v<X.Y.Z> <merge-sha>
git push origin v<X.Y.Z>
```

This is a manual post-merge step in the current MVP. Automated enforcement
(pre-commit hook that requires a tag in the same push, or CI that fails
without a matching tag) is explicitly out of scope for <TICKET-ID> and is a
candidate Phase 4 follow-up.

### 16.7 Cross-references

- §13 Framework Upgrade Playbook — governs upgrading external
  dependencies (pyyaml, jsonschema, anthropic, etc.). §16 governs
  versioning the framework itself. The two are independent: a `Y` bump
  of the framework may or may not coincide with a dependency upgrade.
- `VERSION` file at repository root — the single source of truth.
- `INSTALL.md` § "Framework version" — operator-facing pointer.
- `forge/specs/adrs/adr-004-schema-driven-validation.md` — provides the
  semantic backbone for the X-bump trigger (a breaking schema change is
  defined by the validate-artifact-PASS → FAIL transition on existing
