## 17. Skill Versioning (MANDATORY for any change to `forge/.playbooks/*.md`)

The framework's skills (slash commands in `forge/.playbooks/`) are prompts in production. Treating them as untracked documentation made every edit an unannounced deploy — audit `09-ai-behavior-validation.md` §G2 (HIGH severity). <TICKET-ID> introduces a per-skill SemVer convention so behavior changes are visible at edit time, not at incident time.

### 17.1 Frontmatter contract

Every skill file declares its version via YAML frontmatter at the top:

```yaml
---
version: X.Y.Z
category: lifecycle | utility | operator_helper
last_changed: YYYY-MM-DD
---
```

Then a blank line, then the existing skill body (typically starting with `# Role` or `# Instructions`).

The three required fields are:

| Field | Type | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `version` | SemVer 2.0.0 (X.Y.Z) | Per-skill semantic version. Independent of the framework's overall `VERSION` (per §16). |
| `category` | enum | One of `lifecycle`, `utility`, `operator_helper`. Matches the <TICKET-ID> evals taxonomy (`test_skill_structure.py`). Re-categorization is an X bump (§17.6). |
| `last_changed` | YYYY-MM-DD | Date of the most recent version bump. Updated every time `version` changes. |

### 17.2 SemVer bump rules for skills

| Bump | Trigger |
|---|---|
| **X (major)** | Semantic behavior change. Existing operators must read the changelog entry to understand the new behavior. Examples: `/verify` adds a mandatory verdict; `/plan` changes deviation-classification criteria; `/commit` changes the gate condition. |
| **Y (minor)** | Clarification or addition without behavior change. Examples: refined wording, new examples, new optional section, additional Recommended Follow-up template. Skill produces the same outputs given the same inputs. |
| **Z (patch)** | Typo, format, whitespace, comment-only cleanup. Zero semantic impact. |

### 17.3 When to bump

The bump must happen in the SAME PR as the skill edit. Edits without a corresponding bump fail the <TICKET-ID>-added tests in `forge/evals/static/test_skill_structure.py` at CI. The bump is not optional.

### 17.4 Where to record

Every bump produces:

1. A frontmatter update in the skill file (`version` field bumped; `last_changed` updated to today).
2. An entry in `forge/.playbooks/ (CHANGELOG history TBD)` describing the change + linking the Jira ticket.

### 17.5 Initial version baseline

All 15 skills started at **v1.0.0 on 2026-05-16** (<TICKET-ID>). Skills produced before that date had no version tracking — the first bump after <TICKET-ID> establishes the post-baseline semantic version. <TICKET-ID>'s own /commit is the v1.0.0 release moment.

### 17.6 Category field

Values are constant for the life of a skill. A `lifecycle` skill cannot become `utility` via a Y or Z bump; a re-categorization requires an X (major) bump because:

- The evals harness (`test_skill_structure.py`) applies different structural checks per category. Moving categories changes which checks run.
- Operators interpret category as a constraint on when the skill applies. A category change is a behavior change.

If a re-categorization is genuinely warranted, write an ADR documenting the rationale and reference it from the CHANGELOG entry.

### 17.7 Cross-references

- §16 Framework Versioning — distinct: §16 versions `em-development-framework` as a whole (one `VERSION` file at repo root); §17 versions each skill independently (one `version` field per skill frontmatter).
- <TICKET-ID> evals harness (`forge/evals/static/test_skill_structure.py`) — category taxonomy source; <TICKET-ID> added 3 new test methods that enforce §17.1 frontmatter contract.
- Audit `.lifecycle/artifacts/framework/audits/2026-05-16-full-audit/09-ai-behavior-validation.md` rec 2 (`09:109`) — original requirement; closed by <TICKET-ID>.
- `forge/.playbooks/ (CHANGELOG history TBD)` — operational record of all bumps.

